        "source": "Captain Eryss Vaelor"
      },
      {
        "text": "Prerequisite: 9th level; speed halved, disadvantage on Dex saves, Dex becomes 10; after feeding 4 pints, penalties subside for 1 hour; incompatible with Celerity, Legendary Actions, or Tooth and Claw.",
        "source": "Coagulation"
      },
      {
        "text": "After a successful bite that deals at least 1 damage, the vampire may use a bonus action to drink 1 pint of blood; the target makes a Con save (DC = 8 + Str mod + PB) or is paralyzed while being drained.",
        "source": "Drain (Blood Drain)"
      },
      {
        "text": "For each hit die the target has, roll 1d4 and reduce the target’s maximum HP by the total; the vampire regains that many HP and removes one level of exhaustion.",
        "source": "Drain (Blood Drain)"
      },
      {
        "text": "Repeated draining imposes exhaustion on the target; target dies if max HP reduced below zero, triggering vampirism rules if slain by a True Vampire.",
        "source": "Drain (Blood Drain)"
      },
      {
        "text": "Goran Varus, a High Elf architect turned militia and then was turned into a vampire. He is the meticulous and ruthless overseer of Lady Erliza's subterranean bloodsteel mining operation. Once a gifted architect, the Amn oppression led him to rebellion, he focused his sharp mind into archery and the arcane. Then his vampiric transformation and newfound power warped his precision into a cruel, single-minded focus on resource extraction. He commands his only a couple of Childers he sired that help control and protect the mining line from just beneath Castle Bloodforge to the extents under the Andover Heights mountains. He enforces the thralls labor with an eerie calm, viewing all life as a means to an end. His combat style blends the long-range deadliness of a master archer with the terrifying speed and durability of a high-level vampire.",
        "source": "Goran Varus"
      },
      {
        "text": "Lady Erliza's agents abducted the King of Alaron's son and thwarted a rescue attempt to coerce economic concessions.",
        "source": "Kidnapping of Alaron's prince"
      },
      {
        "text": "Prerequisite: Legendary Actions; on a failed saving throw, choose to succeed instead up to 3 times, resetting on a long rest; at 9th, reset on short rest; at 16th, regain one per turn up to 3.",
        "source": "Legendary Resistance (Vampire)"
      },
      {
        "text": "The Prince of Alaron is held captive by Lady Erliza, with the threat of vampiric transformation if ransom is unpaid.",
        "source": "Prince of Alaron"
      },
      {
        "text": "Sir Darris Gorran is a human Fighter (Cavalier) serving as commander of Castle Bloodforge’s 500-man garrison.",
        "source": "Sir Darris Gorran"
      },
      {
        "text": "He is charmed by Lady Erliza and maintains strict discipline among his men despite moral conflict.",
        "source": "Sir Darris Gorran"
      },
      {
        "text": "Thyra is an aasimar paladin of the Oath of Devotion sworn to Odin.",
        "source": "Thyra Odinson"
      },
      {
        "text": "She suspects Lady Erliza and Shadowfell corruption are intertwined with giant and dragon threats.",
        "source": "Thyra Odinson"
      },
      {
        "text": "What is Vampirism: When a vampire is created the person they were dies. So they don't behave like they did in life but instead are a twisted and inverted version of their former selves. The chaste woman becomes a temptress, the kind man becomes a cruel torturer, and the once holy defender now finds glory in mass death and destruction.",
        "source": "Vampires as a Playable Race"
      },
      {
        "text": "Vampirism isn't lycanthropy, or a curse, or a disease, or any other condition. When a vampire kills you, you die. If you were drained of life by the vampire, then your dead form will be transformed into one of their kind and you will rise as an undead vampire spawn.\nYou will keep the memories of your previous life, your ability scores (which get improved), the knowledge of your skills, proficiencies, feats, and any racial qualities or innate abilities. However, class abilities and spells are usually gone (see keeping class abilities later). Vampirism isn’t an \"effect\" on your character. The person is dead and an evil being (usually) that looks like them now stands in their place. Vampires are largely harsh, merciless, and without compunction. Their tormented souls are twisted in pain. They care not about their previous life or the people in it save using the knowledge and memories to help gain power.\nBecoming a Vampire requires a couple of things 1) being bitten by a Vampire and 2) then being drained of all your hit points and then some (beyond zero) by a Vampire. Even then, the result is a lowly and ravenous vampire spawn.\nVampires in D&D have fairly standard powers and weaknesses but to make them a little more interesting I have expanded beyond those “standard” vampires below. Also, a little variety is nice and I have added some powers and weaknesses in separate sections below that are intended to allow for some customization of your specific playable True Vampire. Note, for the purpose of balancing the playable race you must choose one Vampiric Weakness for each Vampiric Power taken.",
        "source": "Vampires as a Playable Race"
      },
      {
        "text": "Reduces domination over True Vampires to once per day per target for one hour and halves the controlled spawn limit to half hit dice; incompatible with Sireless.",
        "source": "Weakened Bonds"
      }
    ]
